{"type":"result","subtype":"success","is_error":false,"duration_ms":104765,"duration_api_ms":194621,"num_turns":6,"result":"","stop_reason":"end_turn","session_id":"9385134e-866f-490e-8ab8-44336e8b5902","total_cost_usd":0.53085545,"usage":{"input_tokens":4,"cache_creation_input_tokens":28736,"cache_read_input_tokens":82021,"output_tokens":2828,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":28736,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"},"modelUsage":{"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001":{"inputTokens":941,"outputTokens":13247,"cacheReadInputTokens":933927,"cacheCreationInputTokens":63165,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":0.23952495000000004,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":32000},"claude-opus-4-6":{"inputTokens":4,"outputTokens":2828,"cacheReadInputTokens":82021,"cacheCreationInputTokens":28736,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":0.29133050000000005,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":64000}},"permission_denials":[],"structured_output":{"summary":"Examined all four amendments against the actual code. Two identify real correctness/safety issues that should be fixed (terminal replay started_at guard gap, merge field coverage gap). Two propose changes against well-documented, intentional design decisions (owned-String type unification, plan_hash version safety). Agree with all four planner positions.","votes":[{"amendment_id":"fr-6-7bc10021","decision":"reject","rationale":"The amendment self-describes as 'a low-priority observation, not a blocking issue.' Verified in the code that the owned-String approach is explicitly documented as deliberate: structs carry doc comments stating 'Used for both serialization (render) and deserialization (parse) so the field set cannot drift between the model layer and the adapter layer.' The render functions are called only during journal persistence and repair operations — never in a hot path. JSON serialization itself dominates any per-field String allocation. Introducing Cow<'a, str> would add lifetime complexity to structs that also need Clone and serde round-tripping, for zero demonstrated benefit. This is a speculative optimization against a hypothetical future hot path."},{"amendment_id":"fr-6-bcd2cab6","decision":"accept","rationale":"Confirmed a clear data integrity asymmetry in the code. The open-match path (fs.rs ~line 3028-3050) explicitly checks `entries[*index].started_at == started_at` and returns a descriptive error on mismatch, with a comment explaining 'Require started_at to match to avoid backfilling the wrong legacy attempt.' However, the terminal fallback via `unique_terminal_replay_match` (fs.rs ~line 2756-2790) filters only on terminal status, run_id presence, and legacy-start relationships — it never validates started_at. This means a finalized runless attempt with the wrong started_at can have run_id silently backfilled onto it through the terminal path, violating the exact invariant the open-match path was built to enforce. The fix is straightforward: pass started_at into unique_terminal_replay_match and add the same guard, plus a regression test."},{"amendment_id":"fr-6-279a800b","decision":"reject","rationale":"Verified that both existing-row skip locations contain explicit, identical NOTE comments: 'snapshot-based plan_hash backfill is intentionally NOT applied to existing rows. persist_plan() can advance snapshot.plan_hash after the original attempt started, so stamping the current snapshot hash would mislabel a v1 attempt as v2. Only new entry creation auto-populates.' The rationale is sound: in replay/repair flows, the snapshot may reflect a newer plan version than what the attempt actually executed under. Having plan_hash: None (unlabeled) is strictly safer than having a potentially incorrect plan_hash — mislabeling would be a data corruption issue. The amendment incorrectly assumes the snapshot hash is 'canonical' for all attempts, but the code comments explain exactly why that assumption is unsafe."},{"amendment_id":"fr-6-926ed414","decision":"accept","rationale":"Verified a real structural maintenance hazard. Both merge functions (StartJournalDetails::merge and CompletionJournalDetails::merge) use `let mut merged = existing.clone()` then hand-enumerate specific optional fields for conflict detection and backfill. While the render functions have compile-time exhaustiveness (adding a field to the struct without passing it to the constructor is a compile error), the merge functions have no such safeguard. A new optional field added to the shared structs would compile fine, pass existing round-trip serde tests, but be silently ignored during conflict checking in merge — the clone() carries forward whatever existing had, and requested's value for that field is never consulted. In a journal repair codepath where correctness matters most, this is silent data loss. A merge-coverage test (e.g., populate all fields on both sides with distinct values and verify the merge checks all of them) is low-cost and closes this gap."}]},"fast_mode_state":"off","uuid":"328ffa54-d4cd-4b7e-9b66-b1fd03e99e46"}
